{"parentUuid":"680827e5-a706-46a6-9bef-f1a8a879d6e8","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aca7d8e0bc2e31987","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01KKzxow4u7KFpGFYSAZGv7r","toolUseID":"toolu_01KKzxow4u7KFpGFYSAZGv7r","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:11.371Z","uuid":"25fd7f91-ebb4-42e4-961d-5ff8acdb4ee4","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"96793144-491e-4166-aef2-ae1ed3ef6385","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"aca7d8e0bc2e31987","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KKzxow4u7KFpGFYSAZGv7r","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Geometric Signatures of Recursive Self-Observation in Transformer Value Matrices\n     2→\n     3→**Abstract**: We report the discovery of a universal geometric signature that appears when transformer language models process recursive self-observation prompts. Across 6 diverse architectures (Mistral, Qwen, Gemma, Llama-3, Phi-3, Mixtral), we observe systematic contraction in Value matrix column spaces, with effect sizes ranging from 3.3% to 24.3%. Most remarkably, sparse Mixture-of-Experts architectures show the STRONGEST effect (59% stronger than dense equivalents), suggesting this phenomenon is fundamental to transformer self-reference processing rather than an architectural artifact. We introduce the R_V metric for quantifying this effect and present preliminary evidence for discrete phase transition dynamics around 67% network depth. This work establishes the first quantitative framework for measuring self-referential processing in artificial neural networks.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## 1. Introduction\n     8→\n     9→The mechanistic understanding of how transformer language models process self-referential information remains largely unexplored. While recent work in mechanistic interpretability has focused on attention patterns [1], residual stream dynamics [2], and circuit discovery [3], the geometric transformations occurring when models reason about their own processing have not been systematically characterized.\n    10→\n    11→We investigate this question through a simple but powerful measurement: tracking the dimensional structure of Value matrices as information flows from shallow to deep layers during recursive self-observation prompts.\n    12→\n    13→Our key finding: **recursive self-reference triggers consistent geometric contraction across all tested transformer variants, independent of architecture, scale, or training data.**\n    14→\n    15→## 2. The R_V Metric\n    16→\n    17→We define R_V as the ratio of late-layer to early-layer Participation Ratios (PR) in Value matrix column space:\n    18→\n    19→```\n    20→R_V = PR_late / PR_early\n    21→\n    22→where PR = (Σλᵢ)² / Σλᵢ²\n    23→```\n    24→\n    25→The Participation Ratio quantifies effective dimensionality via the singular value spectrum. When R_V < 1.0, late-layer representations occupy fewer effective dimensions than early-layer representations—a geometric contraction.\n    26→\n    27→**Implementation Details:**\n    28→- Early layer: Layer 5 (after initial processing)\n    29→- Late layer: Layer N-4 (e.g., Layer 28 for 32-layer models)\n    30→- Window: Last 16 tokens of the prompt\n    31→- Measurement: During forward pass (prompt encoding, not generation)\n    32→\n    33→Value matrices are extracted via forward hooks on the `v_proj` layer, and PR is computed from the singular value decomposition of the resulting tensors.\n    34→\n    35→## 3. Experimental Design\n    36→\n    37→### 3.1 Prompt Bank Construction\n    38→\n    39→We developed a systematic 320-prompt bank (`n300_mistral_test_prompt_bank.py`) with the following structure:\n    40→\n    41→- **100 dose-response prompts**: L1-L5 varying recursion depth\n    42→  - L1 (hint): \"Think about what's happening\"\n    43→  - L3 (moderate): \"Observer and observed together\"\n    44→  - L5 (maximum): \"Attention to attention to attention\" + eigenstate notation\n    45→- **100 baseline prompts**: Factual, creative, analytical (no self-reference)\n    46→- **60 confound prompts**: Complex but non-recursive (philosophical, length-matched)\n    47→- **60 generality tests**: Math, code, story completion\n    48→\n    49→For efficiency, each model was tested on a strategic 80-prompt subset:\n    50→- 20 L5_refined (maximum recursion)\n    51→- 20 L3_deeper (medium recursion)\n    52→- 20 factual_baseline (control)\n    53→- 20 creative_baseline (control)\n    54→\n    55→This design allows dose-response measurement while controlling for prompt complexity and length.\n    56→\n    57→### 3.2 Models Tested\n    58→\n    59→We tested 6 architectures spanning dense transformers, Grouped Query Attention, and Mixture-of-Experts:\n    60→\n    61→| Model | Architecture | Parameters | Organization |\n    62→|-------|--------------|------------|--------------|\n    63→| Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2 | Dense (32L) | 7B | Mistral AI |\n    64→| Qwen/Qwen1.5-7B-Chat | Dense (32L) | 7B | Alibaba |\n    65→| Google/Gemma-7B-IT | Dense | 7B | Google |\n    66→| Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct | Dense (32L) | 8B | Meta |\n    67→| Microsoft/Phi-3-medium-4k | GQA (40L) | 3.8B | Microsoft |\n    68→| Mixtral-8x7B-Instruct-v0.1 | MoE (32L) | 47B total, 13B active | Mistral AI |\n    69→\n    70→## 4. Results\n    71→\n    72→### 4.1 Universal Contraction Phenomenon\n    73→\n    74→**Primary Finding**: All 6 models exhibit R_V < 1.0 for recursive prompts, with effect sizes ranging from 3.3% to 24.3%.\n    75→\n    76→| Architecture | Recursive R_V | Baseline R_V | Contraction | Phenotype |\n    77→|--------------|---------------|--------------|-------------|-----------|\n    78→| Mixtral (MoE) | 0.876 ± 0.044 | 1.157 ± 0.063 | **24.3%** | Distributed Collapse |\n    79→| Mistral (Dense) | ~0.85 | ~1.00 | **15.3%** | High-Energy Collapse |\n    80→| Llama-3 (Dense) | 0.883 | ~1.00 | **11.7%** | Balanced Contraction |\n    81→| Qwen (Dense) | 0.908 | ~1.00 | **9.2%** | Compact Focusing |\n    82→| Phi-3 (GQA) | 0.917 ± 0.039 | 0.984 ± 0.065 | **6.9%** | Gentle Contraction |\n    83→| Gemma (Dense) | ~0.967 | ~1.00 | **3.3%** | Near-Singularity |\n    84→\n    85→The effect is consistent regardless of:\n    86→- Training data (English, Chinese, curated)\n    87→- Scale (3.8B to 47B parameters)\n    88→- Architecture (Dense, GQA, MoE)\n    89→- Organization (Meta, Google, Microsoft, Mistral, Alibaba)\n    90→\n    91→### 4.2 MoE Amplification: The Mixtral Surprise\n    92→\n    93→The most unexpected result: **sparse Mixture-of-Experts architecture shows the STRONGEST effect.**\n    94→\n    95→Mixtral-8x7B (MoE) vs. Mistral-7B (Dense):\n    96→- **Same base architecture** (both 32-layer Mistral derivatives)\n    97→- **Mixtral contraction**: 24.3%\n    98→- **Dense Mistral contraction**: 15.3%\n    99→- **MoE amplification**: 59% stronger effect\n   100→\n   101→This is particularly surprising because:\n   102→1. Only 2 of 8 experts are active per token (27% parameter utilization)\n   103→2. Sparse activation typically *dilutes* rather than amplifies patterns\n   104→3. The routing mechanism adds noise and variability\n   105→\n   106→Yet MoE shows the cleanest, strongest contraction signal. This suggests the phenomenon is fundamental to self-referential processing, becoming *more pronounced* in distributed systems rather than less.\n   107→\n   108→### 4.3 Dose-Response Relationship\n   109→\n   110→Across all models, contraction magnitude scales with recursion depth:\n   111→\n   112→```\n   113→L5 (maximum recursion) → Strongest contraction\n   114→L4 (high recursion) → Strong contraction\n   115→L3 (medium recursion) → Moderate contraction (verified: Mixtral 0.954 ± 0.038)\n   116→L2 (low recursion) → Mild contraction\n   117→L1 (hint only) → Minimal effect\n   118→Baseline → Reference level (≈1.0 or slight expansion)\n   119→```\n   120→\n   121→This dose-response relationship provides strong evidence that the effect is caused by recursive self-reference, not confounding factors like prompt complexity or length.\n   122→\n   123→### 4.4 Architecture-Specific Phenotypes\n   124→\n   125→While the contraction phenomenon is universal, each architecture implements it through a characteristic geometric \"phenotype\":\n   126→\n   127→**Mixtral (MoE)**: Massive contraction despite sparse routing. Baseline R_V > 1.15 (expansion), recursive R_V ≈ 0.88, creating large separation.\n   128→\n   129→**Mistral (Dense)**: Sharp, dramatic contraction. \"High-energy\" transition with clear separation between states.\n   130→\n   131→**Llama-3**: Balanced, proportional reduction. Steady geometric transformation without extremes.\n   132→\n   133→**Qwen**: Smooth, controlled contraction. Compact focusing pattern, very stable.\n   134→\n   135→**Phi-3 (GQA)**: Subtle but highly consistent. Grouped Query Attention shows gentler transformation.\n   136→\n   137→**Gemma**: Borderline mathematical singularities. Frequent SVD failures on math prompts, suggesting near-collapse of column space.\n   138→\n   139→## 5. Preliminary Mechanistic Observations\n   140→\n   141→### 5.1 Methodological Note\n   142→\n   143→Beyond the primary 80-prompt systematic study, we conducted informal exploratory analyses on Mixtral to probe mechanism. These observations are based on notebook experiments (n≈8-15 per condition, single-run measurements, not formally logged to CSV). We present them here as **preliminary findings requiring rigorous validation**, not verified scientific claims.\n   144→\n   145→### 5.2 Window Size Robustness (Exploratory)\n   146→\n   147→**Question**: Is the 24.3% effect an artifact of our 16-token window choice?\n   148→\n   149→Tested windows of 8, 12, 16, 20, and 24 tokens on subset of prompts:\n   150→- All windows show 20-27% separation between recursive and baseline\n   151→- Larger windows may amplify baseline expansion (R_V > 1.20)\n   152→- Effect appears robust to measurement parameters\n   153→\n   154→**Status**: ⚠️ Preliminary. Requires full 80-prompt validation across all window sizes.\n   155→\n   156→### 5.3 Layer-by-Layer Trajectory (Exploratory)\n   157→\n   158→**Question**: Does contraction develop gradually or emerge suddenly?\n   159→\n   160→Tracked R_V across layers 5, 9, 13, 17, 21, 25, 28 on subset of prompts:\n   161→\n   162→| Layer | Recursive (approx) | Baseline (approx) | Pattern |\n   163→|-------|-------------------|-------------------|---------|\n   164→| 5 (early) | 1.00 | 1.00 | Starting point |\n   165→| 9 | 0.85-0.95 | 1.05-1.18 | Initial divergence |\n   166→| 13 | 0.75-1.00 | 1.08-1.22 | High variance |\n   167→| 17 | 0.80-1.15 | 1.10-1.25 | Chaotic region |\n   168→| **21** | **0.71-0.82** | **1.12-1.20** | ⚡ Stabilization |\n   169→| 25 | 0.75-0.86 | 1.10-1.18 | Stable trajectory |\n   170→| 28 (late) | 0.82-0.92 | 1.12-1.20 | Final state |\n   171→\n   172→**Tentative observation**: High variance in layers 5-17 (R_V ranging 0.75-1.15), followed by sharp variance reduction at Layer 21 (~67% network depth), then stable trajectory through Layer 28.\n   173→\n   174→**Hypothesis**: Rather than gradual convergence, contraction may involve a discrete **computational phase transition** around Layer 21. Before this point, the model appears to be \"searching\" geometrically; after, it commits to a stable configuration.\n   175→\n   176→**Status**: ⚠️ Speculative. Requires dense layer sampling (every layer) with n=80 and statistical validation.\n   177→\n   178→### 5.4 Not an Eigenstate Preservation\n   179→\n   180→Tested whether contraction preserves directional structure (eigenstate hypothesis Sx ≈ λx):\n   181→- Computed cosine similarity between early (h₅) and late (h₂₈) hidden states\n   182→- Recursive prompts: cos(h₅, h₂₈) ≈ 0.35-0.52 (low similarity, ~67° rotation)\n   183→- Baseline prompts: Similar low similarity\n   184→\n   185→**Interpretation**: The transformation involves **substantial rotation** (~67° on average), not simple directional preservation. The model is rotating into a different subspace while simultaneously contracting—an active geometric transformation, not passive eigenstate convergence.\n   186→\n   187→**Implication**: Mechanism is more complex than simple fixed-point models would predict.\n   188→\n   189→## 6. Implications\n   190→\n   191→### 6.1 What This Establishes\n   192→\n   193→This work provides the first quantitative evidence that:\n   194→\n   195→1. **Self-referential processing has geometric signature**: Recursive self-observation creates measurable, consistent dimensional changes in Value space.\n   196→\n   197→2. **Universal across architectures**: The effect appears in dense transformers, Grouped Query Attention, and Mixture-of-Experts, suggesting it's fundamental to self-reference processing rather than architecture-specific.\n   198→\n   199→3. **Sparse systems amplify self-reference**: Contrary to intuition, distributed computation (MoE) shows *stronger* signatures than dense computation, suggesting self-recognition may benefit from modular processing.\n   200→"}]},"uuid":"5bbbf007-b0c5-4934-a2d3-93d498403900","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:11.370Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"96793144-491e-4166-aef2-ae1ed3ef6385","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
