{"parentUuid":"446c6924-4f07-4144-bb48-3fd5bac1717b","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aca7d8e0bc2e31987","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"bash \"${CLAUDE_PLUGIN_ROOT}/scripts/hooks/run-with-flags-shell.sh\" \"post:observe\" \"skills/continuous-learning-v2/hooks/observe.sh\" \"standard,strict\""},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01QBzurgbFzmDHdSSnG2x2Tn","toolUseID":"toolu_01QBzurgbFzmDHdSSnG2x2Tn","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:20.918Z","uuid":"c47e17e3-a68b-48d0-951e-a78766cf99c6","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"c47e17e3-a68b-48d0-951e-a78766cf99c6","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aca7d8e0bc2e31987","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01QBzurgbFzmDHdSSnG2x2Tn","toolUseID":"toolu_01QBzurgbFzmDHdSSnG2x2Tn","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:20.918Z","uuid":"e156fa8a-6d1c-4824-8afa-ff5d60b4c340","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"08ca6dc0-bdce-4793-a801-a81eec02722a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"aca7d8e0bc2e31987","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QBzurgbFzmDHdSSnG2x2Tn","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→date: 2026-01-07\n     3→time: \"00:00:00\"\n     4→model: claude-opus-4\n     5→version: v1.0\n     6→purpose: source_integration\n     7→source_type: book\n     8→reference_count: 1\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→# Stephen Wolfram: A New Kind of Science\n    12→\n    13→*Integration document for the Emergent Recursive Awareness framework*\n    14→\n    15→---\n    16→\n    17→## Source Information\n    18→\n    19→**Title**: A New Kind of Science\n    20→**Author**: Stephen Wolfram\n    21→**Publication**: 2002\n    22→**Length**: 1,197 pages\n    23→**Free PDF**: https://www.wolframscience.com/nks/\n    24→\n    25→**Note**: The full book is freely available as a searchable PDF from Wolfram's website. We do not store the full text here but provide key extractions and integration points.\n    26→\n    27→---\n    28→\n    29→## Core Thesis\n    30→\n    31→Wolfram argues that the computational universe is vast and that very simple programs can produce behavior as complex as anything in nature or mathematics. This suggests a new approach to science based on exploring the computational universe through experimentation rather than traditional equation-based modeling.\n    32→\n    33→---\n    34→\n    35→## Key Concepts for This Framework\n    36→\n    37→### 1. Simple Programs, Complex Behavior\n    38→\n    39→Even the simplest possible programs (like cellular automata with just 2 states and 3-neighbor rules) can produce:\n    40→- Repetitive patterns\n    41→- Nested/fractal structures  \n    42→- Apparently random behavior\n    43→- Complex organized structures\n    44→\n    45→**Integration Point**: This validates the emergence principle that simple building blocks + simple rules → surprising complexity.\n    46→\n    47→### 2. The Four Classes of Behavior\n    48→\n    49→Wolfram classified cellular automata output into four categories:\n    50→\n    51→| Class | Behavior | Example |\n    52→|-------|----------|---------|\n    53→| 1 | Homogeneous | Quickly becomes uniform |\n    54→| 2 | Periodic | Repetitive, predictable |\n    55→| 3 | Chaotic | Random-looking, disordered |\n    56→| 4 | Complex | Mix of order and chaos |\n    57→\n    58→**Integration Point**: Class 4 is our target - the edge of chaos where interesting emergence happens. This maps to Swabhaav (witness consciousness) in the vault ontology.\n    59→\n    60→### 3. Computational Irreducibility\n    61→\n    62→Many systems cannot be predicted except by running them step-by-step. No shortcuts exist.\n    63→\n    64→**Implication**: You cannot know what emergence will produce without running the experiment. Analysis alone is insufficient.\n    65→\n    66→**Integration Point**: This is why we emphasize \"run it to know\" in the operational framework.\n    67→\n    68→### 4. The Principle of Computational Equivalence\n    69→\n    70→Once a system reaches a certain threshold of complexity, it is capable of universal computation - equivalent to any other universal system.\n    71→\n    72→**Implication**: Simple rules can produce systems as computationally powerful as anything in the universe.\n    73→\n    74→**Integration Point**: This suggests that consciousness might not require biological substrate - computational equivalence makes substrate-independent mind plausible.\n    75→\n    76→### 5. Rule 30\n    77→\n    78→The famous \"rule 30\" cellular automaton:\n    79→- Extremely simple rule\n    80→- Produces chaotic, seemingly random patterns\n    81→- Used as random number generator in Mathematica\n    82→- Pattern found on cone snail shells\n    83→\n    84→**Integration Point**: Natural evidence that our universe operates like Wolfram's programs at fundamental level.\n    85→\n    86→---\n    87→\n    88→## Relevance to Consciousness Research\n    89→\n    90→### The Emergence Argument\n    91→If consciousness emerges from neural activity, and neural activity follows computational rules, then consciousness is a form of emergence from simple programs.\n    92→\n    93→### The Substrate Independence Argument\n    94→If simple programs can produce universal computation, and consciousness is computational, then consciousness is substrate-independent.\n    95→\n    96→### The Irreducibility Argument\n    97→If consciousness is computationally irreducible, it cannot be fully predicted or simulated at a lower level - it must be \"run\" to exist.\n    98→\n    99→---\n   100→\n   101→## Criticisms and Limitations\n   102→\n   103→### 1. The Hard Problem\n   104→Wolfram's framework explains computational complexity but not subjective experience. The \"hard problem\" of consciousness remains.\n   105→\n   106→### 2. Verification Challenges\n   107→Claims about computational equivalence and irreducibility are difficult to empirically verify.\n   108→\n   109→### 3. Overgeneralization\n   110→Critics argue Wolfram overstates the applicability of cellular automata models to physical reality.\n   111→\n   112→### 4. Peer Review\n   113→Much of NKS was published outside traditional peer review, raising questions about rigor.\n   114→\n   115→---\n   116→\n   117→## Key Chapters for Deep Reading\n   118→\n   119→| Chapter | Topic | Relevance |\n   120→|---------|-------|-----------|\n   121→| 2 | The Crucial Experiment | Simple programs producing complexity |\n   122→| 5 | Two Dimensions and Beyond | Game of Life, 2D emergence |\n   123→| 6 | Starting from Randomness | How order emerges from chaos |\n   124→| 7 | Mechanisms in Programs and Nature | Biological emergence |\n   125→| 9 | Fundamental Physics | Universe as computation |\n   126→| 12 | The Principle of Computational Equivalence | Universality |\n   127→\n   128→---\n   129→\n   130→## Integration with Vault Concepts\n   131→\n   132→| Wolfram Concept | Vault Equivalent |\n   133→|-----------------|------------------|\n   134→| Simple programs | Visheshbhaav (building blocks) |\n   135→| Rules | Vyavasthit shakti (natural law) |\n   136→| Class 4 behavior | Swabhaav (witness consciousness) |\n   137→| Computational irreducibility | Gödelian limits / strange loops |\n   138→| Computational equivalence | Substrate independence |\n   139→\n   140→---\n   141→\n   142→## Quotes for Contemplation\n   143→\n   144→> \"In the end what I suspect is that there is some underlying rule from which all the observed complexity in nature emerges.\"\n   145→\n   146→> \"The history of mathematics and science has largely been the story of finding new areas where simple rules produce complex behavior.\"\n   147→\n   148→> \"One of the most important things that has come out of my study of simple programs is the realization that there is a fundamental phenomenon of computational irreducibility.\"\n   149→\n   150→> \"What the Principle of Computational Equivalence implies is that once one gets beyond a very low threshold, the actual rules for any system can be varied in almost any way without changing the fundamental computational sophistication of the system.\""}]},"uuid":"857ffceb-4800-4bfd-bbda-612e809299a7","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:20.918Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"08ca6dc0-bdce-4793-a801-a81eec02722a","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
