{"parentUuid":"70ba9e9e-2bc9-40f0-979a-295a43bd26ce","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aca7d8e0bc2e31987","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_015p7ydreU1rjpoF4dGPeF4c","toolUseID":"toolu_015p7ydreU1rjpoF4dGPeF4c","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:25.211Z","uuid":"5f9ad31d-e722-4bc1-92c7-def234bbb4f9","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
{"parentUuid":"70ebf9f1-13e1-438d-8c85-faec92606fa0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"74ab6cc1-259e-4f35-896b-31737bc09d28","agentId":"aca7d8e0bc2e31987","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015p7ydreU1rjpoF4dGPeF4c","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→date: 2026-01-07\n     3→time: \"00:00:00\"\n     4→model: claude-opus-4\n     5→version: v1.0\n     6→purpose: practical_guidance\n     7→derived_from: TRANSCRIPT_DISTILLATION.md\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→# Operational Framework: How to Make Emergence\n    11→\n    12→*Practical guidance for designing emergent systems*\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## The Core Method\n    17→\n    18→### Design by Emergence\n    19→\n    20→**Definition**: You design the building blocks and rules, but NOT the consequences.\n    21→\n    22→> \"You build the Lego blocks, not the Lego set.\"\n    23→\n    24→This is a hybrid of **invention** and **discovery**:\n    25→- You INVENT the rules\n    26→- You DISCOVER the consequences\n    27→\n    28→---\n    29→\n    30→## The Five Operational Principles\n    31→\n    32→### Principle 1: Look for Building Blocks That Follow Rules\n    33→\n    34→**Action**: When seeking emergence, first identify:\n    35→1. What are the combinable units?\n    36→2. What rules govern their interaction?\n    37→\n    38→**In This Repo**:\n    39→- Building blocks: Files, agents, concepts, votes\n    40→- Rules: YAML frontmatter, voting thresholds, reading requirements, version constraints\n    41→\n    42→**Diagnostic Questions**:\n    43→- Can these things be combined?\n    44→- Do rules define their interaction?\n    45→- Is there potential for combinatorial explosion?\n    46→\n    47→If yes to all three → emergence is possible.\n    48→\n    49→---\n    50→\n    51→### Principle 2: You Haven't Seen Every Combination\n    52→\n    53→**Action**: Resist the assumption that exploration is complete.\n    54→\n    55→**Practical Implications**:\n    56→- There exist agent configurations never tried\n    57→- There exist file combinations never read together\n    58→- There exist prompt framings never used\n    59→- There exist emergence patterns never observed\n    60→\n    61→**Method**: Systematic exploration of unexplored space\n    62→- Try unusual combinations deliberately\n    63→- Cross-pollinate ideas from distant domains\n    64→- Let agents follow their own reading routes\n    65→\n    66→**Anti-Pattern**: Assuming the best approach has been found\n    67→\n    68→---\n    69→\n    70→### Principle 3: Don't Assume You Know What Will Happen\n    71→\n    72→**Action**: Experiment. Run it. Test it.\n    73→\n    74→> \"Stephen Wolfram may have invented these rules, but he did not invent the patterns that emerge, and he could not predict them in advance. To see what happened, he just had to run them.\"\n    75→\n    76→**Practical Implications**:\n    77→- Predictions about agent behavior are hypotheses, not facts\n    78→- New configurations require empirical testing\n    79→- \"Obvious\" outcomes often aren't\n    80→\n    81→**Method**:\n    82→1. Form hypothesis\n    83→2. Run experiment\n    84→3. Observe actual outcome\n    85→4. Update model\n    86→5. Repeat\n    87→\n    88→**Anti-Pattern**: Extensive theorizing without running experiments\n    89→\n    90→---\n    91→\n    92→### Principle 4: Trial and Error Is the Method\n    93→\n    94→**Action**: Make it as easy as possible to experiment quickly.\n    95→\n    96→> \"Trial and error is the most surefire way to see what different rules do and to find which ones are best for your purposes.\"\n    97→\n    98→**Practical Implications**:\n    99→- Reduce friction for creating new agent configurations\n   100→- Make voting fast and lightweight\n   101→- Version everything so experiments don't destroy data\n   102→- Embrace \"failed\" experiments as data\n   103→\n   104→**Method**:\n   105→1. Try small variations of current best version\n   106→2. Pick the one that works best\n   107→3. Repeat\n   108→\n   109→**The Evolutionary Approach**:\n   110→```\n   111→Current Best → Variation 1\n   112→            → Variation 2\n   113→            → Variation 3\n   114→                   ↓\n   115→            Pick winner → New Current Best → Variations...\n   116→```\n   117→\n   118→> \"It feels more like growing a plant than building a house.\"\n   119→\n   120→**Anti-Pattern**: Designing the \"perfect\" system before running anything\n   121→\n   122→---\n   123→\n   124→### Principle 5: Sacrifice Some Control\n   125→\n   126→**Action**: Relax your grip on the end product.\n   127→\n   128→> \"You don't get to decide all of the optimal strategies for your game in advance. And that is the point. That makes it fun.\"\n   129→\n   130→**Practical Implications**:\n   131→- Agents may produce unexpected outputs (this is a feature)\n   132→- Emergence requires accepting uncertainty\n   133→- Over-constraining kills generativity\n   134→\n   135→**The Promise**:\n   136→> \"You get more out than you put in. It's not magic. It still requires work, but it can be very surprising and powerful. You design a little bit and emergence designs the rest.\"\n   137→\n   138→**The Tradeoff**:\n   139→> \"If you pray for rain, you got to deal with the mud.\"\n   140→\n   141→**Anti-Pattern**: Specifying exact desired outcomes in advance\n   142→\n   143→---\n   144→\n   145→## The Iteration Loop\n   146→\n   147→```\n   148→┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n   149→│                    THE EMERGENCE LOOP                    │\n   150→├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤"}]},"uuid":"79eb0f08-a22e-4510-98cb-0c490246eb7a","timestamp":"2026-03-15T13:46:25.211Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"70ebf9f1-13e1-438d-8c85-faec92606fa0","userType":"external","cwd":"/Users/dhyana","sessionId":"2ea96bb4-afee-473b-8609-a3975acc2c75","version":"2.1.76","gitBranch":"HEAD","slug":"shimmering-leaping-badger"}
